{"text": " I have a question. What's the biggest asteroid that ever hit Earth? Turns out the one that hit the dinosaurs wasn't that big. On the very small scale, you have asteroids that are as tiny as a dog all the way up to the size of a building, and there are likely millions of these closer to us than Mars, and they hit us all the time. But our atmosphere protects us, but then there are the city killers. These are about the size of a building to about two city blocks. When one of these hit Earth in 1908, it only glanced off our atmosphere, and it still released the equivalent of 15 megatons of TNT, and flattened 80 million trees. But then one size up is country killer, and then anything bigger than that, they call a planet killer. It would change all life on Earth forever. The rock that hit the dinosaurs was roughly 10 kilometers across, but 1.8 billion years ago, a nearly 15 kilometer wide rock slammed into what's now Canada, and 170 million years before that. The largest asteroid we have evidence of hitting Earth, 20 kilometers wide, struck what is now South Africa. But good news, we found about 99% of the biggest asteroids near us, but the city and country killers, that's the biggest hole in Earth's defenses right now. To find out how people are trying to fix it, follow along.", "segments": [{"id": 0, "seek": 0, "start": 0.0, "end": 3.84, "text": " I have a question. What's the biggest asteroid that ever hit Earth?", "tokens": [50364, 286, 362, 257, 1168, 13, 708, 311, 264, 3880, 33833, 300, 1562, 2045, 4755, 30, 50556], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10258617401123046, "compression_ratio": 1.7781456953642385, "no_speech_prob": 0.004892634227871895}, {"id": 1, "seek": 0, "start": 3.84, "end": 7.44, "text": " Turns out the one that hit the dinosaurs wasn't that big.", "tokens": [50556, 29524, 484, 264, 472, 300, 2045, 264, 25851, 2067, 380, 300, 955, 13, 50736], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10258617401123046, "compression_ratio": 1.7781456953642